<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,1302,1977]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,268,1410,1436]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Mine.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[284,366,1411,1437]" captionStart="FIGURES 67–74" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[163,1422,194,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-15@27.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 67–74. Figures 67–70: Amauromyza (Cephalomyza) flavifrons (Meigen); 67: mine in Silene latifolia subsp. alba leaf; 68–69: posterior segments of puparium; 68: lateral view; 69: posterior view. 70: posterior spiracles (posterior view). Figures 71–74: Aulagromyza populi (Kaltenbach); 71: mines in Populus nigra leaf; 72–73: posterior segments of puparium; 72: lateral view; 73: posterior view. 74: posterior spiracles (posterior view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158617" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158617/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 71</figureCitation>
) The solitary larva forms a yellow wide irregular linear mine. When several larvae feed on one leaf, mines can unite and appear as a single blotch mine. Pupation takes place within the mine with the puparium overwintering.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,1302,1977]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1518,1544]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Puparium.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[342,476,1519,1545]" captionStart="FIGURES 67–74" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1867,1891]" captionTargetBox="[163,1422,194,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-15@27.[151,1435,181,1844]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 67–74. Figures 67–70: Amauromyza (Cephalomyza) flavifrons (Meigen); 67: mine in Silene latifolia subsp. alba leaf; 68–69: posterior segments of puparium; 68: lateral view; 69: posterior view. 70: posterior spiracles (posterior view). Figures 71–74: Aulagromyza populi (Kaltenbach); 71: mines in Populus nigra leaf; 72–73: posterior segments of puparium; 72: lateral view; 73: posterior view. 74: posterior spiracles (posterior view)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158617" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158617/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Figs. 72–74</figureCitation>
) Brownish-orange, glossy, 
<quantity box="[780,865,1519,1545]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" unit="mm" value="2.4">2.4 mm</quantity>
long, with weak segmentation; surface finely wrinkled except for wide spine bands. Posterior spiracles set on narrow and short conical protuberances entirely strongly separate; with numerous small sessile bulbs set around central larger bulb. Anal plate slightly protruding above the surface of the puparium viewed from the side and directed ventro-posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,1302,1977]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,548,1662,1689]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Cephalopharyngeal skeleton.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[565,662,1663,1689]" captionStart="FIGURES 377–382" captionStartId="104.[151,264,1818,1842]" captionTargetBox="[177,1433,187,1777]" captionTargetId="figure-18@104.[151,1435,181,1794]" captionTargetPageId="104" captionText="FIGURES 377–382. Aulagromyza populi (Kaltenbach); 377: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 378: frontal view of head; 379: head viewed from the side; 380: oviscape and spermatheca proportionally; 381: proctiger; 382 a–b: ventral receptacle; a: lateral view; b: view from behind." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158748" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158748/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Fig. 377</figureCitation>
) Right mouthhook much larger than the left, each with ventral portion distinctly abducted and bearing two accessory teeth. Intermediate sclerite narrow and long, 1.32× as long as maximum height of left mouthhook. The mouthhook, the intermediate sclerite ventrally, anterior portion of the pharyngeal sclerite and the dorsal cornu posteriorly are strongly sclerotized; the intermediate sclerite dorsally, central portion of the dorsal cornu and ventral cornu are much less so. The dorsal cornu bears an oval “closed” window, and the ventral cornu bears a small and narrow “closed” window. Indentation index 80.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,1302,1977]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,360,1879,1905]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Female head.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[378,545,1879,1905]" captionStart="FIGURES 377–382" captionStartId="104.[151,264,1818,1842]" captionTargetBox="[177,1433,187,1777]" captionTargetId="figure-18@104.[151,1435,181,1794]" captionTargetPageId="104" captionText="FIGURES 377–382. Aulagromyza populi (Kaltenbach); 377: cephalopharyngeal skeleton; 378: frontal view of head; 379: head viewed from the side; 380: oviscape and spermatheca proportionally; 381: proctiger; 382 a–b: ventral receptacle; a: lateral view; b: view from behind." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158748" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158748/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Figs. 378, 379</figureCitation>
) Yellowish-orange, with arista black and oc tr ginger medially; orbit strongly projecting above eye in profile, 2 orb s, 2 fr s; lunule higher than a semicircle, narrowing posteriorly, reaching the level of the posterior fr s; pped large, flattened anteriorly; gena medially 0.34× as high as maximum height of eye.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5158617" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5158617" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5158617/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="28" startId="27.[151,264,1867,1891]" targetBox="[163,1422,194,1831]" targetPageId="27">
